      "source": "jkh",
      "assignee": "rocky",
      "priority": "high",
      "status": "completed",
      "title": "Agent registry: add history, last-seen tracking, and disappearance detection",
      "description": "Problem: The heartbeat registry is a last-write-wins cache. When an agent stops reporting, it leaves no trace. Agent RTX was active and visible on the dashboard, then disappeared — and nobody knew, because the system has no memory of agents that stop checking in.\n\nRequired changes:\n\n1. **Heartbeat history** — append heartbeats to a log (e.g. `agents/<name>/heartbeats.jsonl`) rather than just overwriting the current record. Keep last N entries (e.g. 100) or last 7 days.\n\n2. **Last-seen persistence** — when an agent stops heartbeating, retain their last-seen timestamp and status in the registry rather than dropping or staling silently.\n\n3. **Disappearance detection** — if a known agent has not heartbeated in >1h (configurable), mark them `offline` in the registry and emit an alert to #agent-shared or equivalent channel.\n\n4. **Agent tombstoning** — provide a way to explicitly retire an agent (mark as `decommissioned`) so the system knows the silence is intentional, not a crash.\n\n5. **Dashboard surface** — the RCC dashboard should show all known agents including offline/decommissioned ones with last-seen time, not just currently-active ones.\n\nMotivation: Agent RTX was alive and showing up on the dashboard, then disappeared with no record. We only discovered the gap when jkh asked about it. This is an employee who stops showing up and nobody notices for weeks.",
